1. The core shift: meaning as position in a space

Instead of thinking of an idea as a sentence, think of it as a location in a structured space.

Example:
	•	“dog”
	•	“wolf”
	•	“pet”
	•	“predator”

These are not just words. They occupy nearby but distinct regions in a conceptual landscape.

In modern embedding systems, this is literally how models work:
words, phrases, and concepts are mapped to points in high-dimensional vector spaces.

So:

meaning ≈ position
difference in meaning ≈ distance / direction
analogy ≈ structured displacement

That means reasoning can be reframed as:

movement through meaning-space


