3. The five core geometric primitives of meaning

To reason about meaning geometrically, you only need a few primitives.

A. Points

A point is a specific concept, state, or encoded meaning.

Examples:
	•	justice
	•	red
	•	fatherhood
	•	entropy
	•	betrayal

B. Distance

Distance measures dissimilarity or effort required to transform one idea into another.

Examples:
	•	“dog” is closer to “wolf” than to “chair”
	•	“mercy” may be closer to “forgiveness” than to “accounting”

Distance can mean:
	•	semantic difference
	•	translation difficulty
	•	cognitive effort
	•	emotional distance
	•	logical transform cost

C. Direction

Direction means how one idea changes into another.

Example:

king - man + woman ≈ queen

That is a directional transform.

Direction can encode:
	•	gender shift
	•	time shift
	•	abstraction shift
	•	moral polarity
	•	scale shift
	•	domain shift

D. Curvature

Curvature measures how straight or distorted movement is in the space.

High curvature means:
	•	tiny changes lead to big interpretive shifts
	•	reasoning becomes unstable
	•	analogy breaks easily
	•	the terrain is deceptive or nonlinear

Low curvature means:
	•	relationships are smooth
	•	interpolation works well
	•	analogies transfer cleanly

E. Boundaries

Boundaries separate regions where meanings stop being interchangeable.

Examples:
	•	joke vs threat
	•	metaphor vs literal claim
	•	lawful analogy vs category error
	•	science vs allegory

A lot of confusion is really boundary failure.

