5. Why tensors matter

A vector stores one list of coordinates.
A matrix stores pairwise relations.
A tensor stores relations across multiple modes.

Meaning is naturally multi-modal.

You often need to represent:
	•	concept
	•	relation
	•	time
	•	context
	•	certainty
	•	perspective
	•	scale
	•	modality

That naturally wants tensor structure.

For example:

MeaningTensor[entity_A, relation, entity_B, domain, time, certainty]

Example:

[speculation, increases, volatility, finance, long_horizon, medium_confidence]

This lets you manipulate meaning formally.

You can:
	•	compress
	•	rotate
	•	project
	•	marginalize
	•	cluster
	•	interpolate
	•	detect contradiction
	•	trace invariants across domains

