7. Memory becomes topology, not storage

This is a very important deeper idea.

Memory is not just “items in a box.”
Memory is often better understood as shape in a space.

You remember something better when it has:
	•	many connections
	•	strong gradients
	•	distinctive shape
	•	emotional charge
	•	retrieval paths from multiple directions

In other words, a memory is easier to recover when it sits on a well-connected manifold.

This means forgetting is not always deletion.
Sometimes it is:
	•	pathway loss
	•	flattening of gradients
	•	boundary collapse
	•	interference from nearby regions
	•	compression beyond reversibility

So memory systems should not only store content.
They should preserve:
	•	relation shape
	•	access paths
	•	invariants under re-expression

This lines up very strongly with your stitching idea.

The embroidery can change, but the stitching must preserve retrieval geometry.

