9. Logic as allowed motion

Logic can be understood as a set of rules about which moves preserve structure.

For example:

If A implies B, and B implies C, then moving from A to C is permitted.

In geometric terms:
logic defines valid geodesics, or lawful paths, through meaning-space.

Fallacies are then geometric distortions such as:
	•	shortcutting across an invalid bridge
	•	projecting across the wrong axis
	•	confusing adjacency with identity
	•	transporting structure across a broken boundary
	•	treating local curvature as global truth

This is why arguments often feel like “something is off” before you can name the flaw.
You are sensing geometric incoherence.

