10. Contradiction as incompatible geometry

A contradiction can be seen as a point that cannot occupy the same region under the same constraints.

Example:

A = “This policy increases freedom.”
B = “This policy removes all voluntary choice.”

If “freedom” and “removes voluntary choice” occupy incompatible regions under the same domain and timescale, the geometry tears.

This is why contradiction auditing is not just symbolic.
It can be thought of as checking for manifold inconsistency.

That aligns strongly with your Mirror / Hypatia ideas.

