14. Abstraction is quotienting the space

One of the deepest mathematical intuitions here:
abstraction means grouping many states into one equivalence class.

Example:
	•	robin
	•	eagle
	•	sparrow

collapse into:
	•	bird

So abstraction is like quotienting the space by an equivalence relation.

This is powerful because it reduces complexity.
But it is also dangerous because every abstraction hides differences.

So every abstraction is a bargain:
	•	gain compression
	•	lose resolution

This is one reason strong reasoning requires reversible zooming.
You need to move up and down the abstraction ladder without getting lost.

That fits your Reversibility Gate instinct very well.

